segments.text: a sit-in vigil at the Minnesota State Capitol over Thanksgiving Day where we fasted and conducted a memorial prayer.
One of the local peace activists and clergy and laymen concerned, a Lutheran minister from Minneapolis came over and we prayed and the television cameras came and we got good press.
And we were generally trying to do those less obtrusive things.
And we felt like we were reaching a greater number of people, because they wanted to sit down and talk with us, because that's the image we carefully radiated.
Well, having mentioned the election, it's been said that McGovern was the anti-war candidate and had the support of the anti-war movement.
Does that hold true with the Vietnam Vets Against the War, at least in your region?
Hubert Humphrey was his main opponent for the Democratic nomination that year.
Hubert's from the Twin Cities.
Hubert's been a long time strong DFL person.
What's a DFL?
Democrat Farmer Labor.
The Democratic Party in this area has been called the Democrat Farmer Labor for a number of years to indicate its popular grassroots level support.
A number of veterans felt that in 68, Hubert had changed his position of supporting the war and supporting LBJ.

That he was forced into supporting LBJ because he was a vice presidential candidate, because he was a vice president, and he believed that the vice president ought to either be on the president's side or should resign.
And so there was some support for, among the vets, for
Hubert, but I'd say it was probably 5% of the vets who were active in the political caucuses that year.
Otherwise, 95% of the vets, in my guesstimation, supported McGovern.
And once he was officially the representative of the Democratic Party, did the vets engage in campaign reform?
Yes, yes.
The VVAW organization engaged in
in campaigning for him.
At this time, on the Mankato State campus, on the university campus, and also at a national level, there were two other veterans' organizations.
One had been financed by the Republicans, and I don't... Vietnam Veterans for Peace, or Vietnam Veterans...
I don't remember what their title is.
I'd have to look that up.
But they had the three-piece suit, pinstripe person who would go around and try to heckle us, and do those kind of things, and come up with facts and figures.
They were basically a reaction by the Republicans.
The Republicans established this group, just like the Dirty Tricks group the Republicans established.
Like the Hard Hats?
Were they Hard Hats?
Yeah.
Or I'm saying like the Hardhats.
Well, like the Hardhats, yes.
They just went around on campus and presented themselves to be college students who agreed with the war.
Plus there was a national organization of just vets who were attempting to be apolitical.
Did you, by early 73, the BBAW and others
sort of outlined a platform that always seemed to include a national campaign for the impeachment of Nixon.
Did that play a part at all?
Now this is getting close to when maybe you pulled out or when you left the VBAW.
Well, through the election, through the election of Carter, I worked with the vets.
What happened in our area is after Carter was elected, no one
Let's see.
Wait a second.
I'm sorry.
I'm getting confused here.
After McGovern was so badly beaten by Nixon, and after the Watergate came to a head and Nixon resigned, the organization basically folded.
By that time, everyone had experienced burnout.
The radicals in the non-
veteran peace organizations had began to take over, and the more moderate folks dropped out.
Okay, so with the withdrawal of Nixon then, is it just the Minnesota chapter or the five-state region chapter that folded, or pretty much all around?
Well, the five-state region in Minnesota folded, and that was the...
the twilight of the national organization.
The urgency which created the organization had diminished, and the organization basically folded.
Well, after all, in 73, the troops, the last American troops had already come back, so it seems to me the major cause, or one of the major causes, had already been remedied.
Okay.
Did you...
Through your time either as a member or as regional director, have any feeling that there might be some FBI infiltration with what was going on?
Yes, on a number of occasions.
I believe the first time that I personally suspected someone that I was associating with to be
to be a plant of some sort was after a meeting of the Mankato area peace organizations over at my apartment in Mankato.
We met early one evening and kind of partied on into toward midnight that night.
Got up the next morning and attended classes.
I came home about noon the next day and found my back door open.
Apparently someone who had been at that meeting had unbolted, it was just a deadbolt, had unbolted the door which was positioned behind the refrigerator in the kitchen.
We never used the door and it was just an emergency exit to us.
They'd unbolted the door and came back that morning knowing I would be at class.
because the refrigerator was slightly ajar and the door was unbolted.
The refrigerator had been moved about four inches out of place, and I thought, geez, when did this happen?

And I got nosing around, didn't think too much of it, moved the refrigerator back into place, and then I noticed that eight to 10, 12 glasses that we'd been drinking from the evening before were missing, and that a ceramic ashtray
which I had just purchased two or three days earlier in anticipation of smoking at this meeting, was missing.
And we talked about that with some of the other folks in the organization.
We decided that because about a month, three weeks prior to this meeting, the regional law enforcement center, which was being built in Mankato, had been bombed one evening.
And I guess $120,000 damage somewhere in that area was done.
And the clock that was supposedly used to time the blast had been the clock that had the Secretary of the Student Senate from Mankato State.
It was her clock on her desk.
She was the first cousin of my wife.

And I had spent a lot of time up at the Student Senate, and I had, upon coming back from Vietnam, I had applied for unemployment benefits, and one of the skills that I'd listed was as a demolition expert.
And we began to put two and two together, and thought that, you know, unbeknownst to me, I had become a suspect, and that they were looking for fingerprints of the people that were at the meeting.
Another occasion was when this person that I suspected to be the agent, first time I ever laid eyes on him was St. Patty's Day of that year, when there were two campuses.
There was an upper campus, which was the newer emerging developing campus at Mankato State,
with the lower campus of Old Main and some other buildings.
There was a bus shuttle system which shuttled students regularly up and down the hill.
But hitchhiking was by far the prevalent means of transportation.
And hitchhikers generally waited in a certain area to go between campuses.
And as cars would stop, you'd jump in.
And if there was room, you got in.
And you waited till the next one if it was filled.
And this guy hops into my van, this person that I later suspected.
And he says, St. Paddy's Day.
He said, I'm going to go down to Kilkenny, Minnesota, which is where I'm from.
I'm going to go down to Kilkenny, Minnesota and have a few beers.
That's St. Paddy's Day.
I'm looking for some folks.
I'm wondering if anybody's going that way.
And then this guy, I bumped shoulders with him pretty regularly thereafter.
And I think he even played racquetball with him on a number of occasions.
But nothing ever came out of that then?
Well, I think he was the operative.
And he eventually worked his way into a position within the organization.
And everyone kind of didn't know what to think of him.
They didn't want to suspect him of being an agent and alienate him if it wasn't true.
And we didn't have any hard evidence.
And he really wasn't proposing radical things.
It just seemed like he wanted to gather information
And we all thought that there really wasn't any harm in that.
Any other occasions?
Yeah.
Another occasion was when a gal came up to me, a red-haired gal from out east, and she had on hippie bib overhauls.
She said she was driving, she was going out west to live in a commune, and her van broke down here in Mankato, and so she decided to enroll at school.
and make some money and repair the van.
And she was just really impressed by a speech I'd given that morning over at one of the campuses, or schools, high schools in the area.
And could, you know, could we talk about it?
So we sat down in the Union and had coffee.
And she, you know, indicated that she would be enormously pleased if I went over to her house and got to know her a little better.
And I was extremely flattered and caught somewhat off guard and really thought that she was really attracted to me.
At the end of the conversation, when I decided not to come over and declined going with her, was, well, can you put me in touch with any Communist Party members here?
I'm really into this and I want to do my thing on a serious level.
And of course, that was the first opportunity that I'd had to really think that there were legitimate card-carrying commies around.
That summer, this was in the spring of 72, that summer, I attended a summer session at Harvard.
I happened to be sitting in a Zum Zum's coffee ice cream sandwich parlor,

about a half of a block off of Harvard Square, and I saw her come in and purchase an ice cream cone, and she had on an expensive tweed, very British, English, Harvard, Bostonian, well-to-do suit, and she was doing something at Harvard.
I was going to approach her and say, hey, how are you doing, and I thought,
God, if it just appears that she was into something and I don't know who she was, maybe they don't know I'm here.
I don't want to cause any trouble.
Speaking of communists, some suggest that there was a pro-communist, pro-North Vietnam element in the anti-war movement.
Yes.
In the Minnesota region, that was clearly not true.
We were populists who believed in the Constitution and in the democratic process.
And we wanted to engage in debates and talk to people and inform them of our opinion so they could make their decisions.
because we felt the government and the military were not giving all the data.
On the national level, the VVAW members were infinitely more radical than we were.
We withdrew because of that.
They used the bourgeois proletariat lingo and jargon.
They were extremely radical in appearance with the afros, white guys with the afros and beards.
grubby, smelly clothes and spouting slogans instead of engaging in discourse.

We withdrew, and I think John Kerry ultimately got out of the organization because we felt that it had been taken over by people who did not represent what we wanted represented, that they were radical.
It was very possible that inside their heads they thought they identified with certain aspects
socialist or communist party.
I don't know that that was the case nationally.
Some go so far as to say that these communist elements were actually being directed from Moscow.
I don't know.
We suspected that one of the radical people on the national board of VVAW was actually an FBI plant.
And he would occasionally propose things that I thought were outlandishly radical and would ultimately be extremely detrimental to the peace movement.
And the rest of the folks there, a great number of others, didn't seem to have jobs, but yet seemed to be able to fly around the country and live a
live a lifestyle.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I've thought about that many times after that meeting in Kansas City, but I've never had any hardcore evidence.
Okay.
Well, along with this pro-communist element, Norman Podhoretz cites two other
themes or elements comprising the BBAW as well as just anti-war movements in general.
And one is the anti-anti-communist attitude.
Was that prevalent with your group?
That is the attitude that rejects the monolithic communist and is anti the better dead than red attitude.
Um...
There were certain people in the local region who believed that, or who felt that it may not necessarily be better to be dead than red.
Maybe I didn't make that clear enough.
The anti-anti-communists, didn't most of you share that attitude, that over detente spirit, rejecting the notion that communism is the world menace?
And that suggests in itself that that attitude may have been one of the reasons for getting into NOM in the first place.
I think that the prevalent attitude was that communism was not so monolithic, and that communism was, but yet communism was generally evil.
of some nature.
But on the other hand, if in a free democratic election people chose to do things that were more philosophically communist, that was their business.
If those folks in other countries wanted to live that way, that really was their business.
Okay.
And the third gang was an anti-American, or
sometimes called anti-imperialist, at least in their terms, aspect.
Did you find that in your region?
Not in the region.
There were occasional people who talked that way.
But at the national level?
At the national level, that was probably the prevalent attitude.
Really?
was the terms that they could speak out most on.
How strongly they identify with any other political organization such as the Commies, I don't know.
But anti-imperialism was a big, big issue.
And when that issue was growing, that's when you all withdrew then.
About that same time?
Yeah.
The anti-imperialist issue had been around for quite a while, and we basically agreed with them that we ought not to be imperialist.
It was just a matter of, is it imperialist to go in and preserve a democracy?
Well, if you read the VBAW today, or let's say 1982, they now...

went ahead to attach the anti-imperialist slogan at the end, it's no longer the VBAW, but it's the VBAWAI, that would tend to suggest that most of the conservative elements, indeed when you read the paper, most of the conservative elements are no longer there.
It's more of an anti-imperialist, any U.S. action seems to be viewed as an imperialist gesture now.
Seems a little bit more like the radicals took over now?
Yeah, I think very clearly they have.
most other people after the withdrawal of American troops that for whatever reasons I've got to get my own personal life in order.
I've got to graduate from college or get my job or get back in the swing and start to lead a normal life.
There are very few people who continued on in a political vein of this sort outside of the major parties.
Most of us were assimilated into
attending caucuses and voting and involving ourselves in some political organization.
But for about six, eight years, I heard or read nothing or had no contact with any organization of VBAW.
And this latest resurfacing, I really don't know what they stand for.

Well, in 1982, they were in direct opposition to the building of the memorial that was put up in Washington, saying that what that was was a slap in the face to the anti-war movement and a preparation to get some more 18-year-old boys ready to go for some imperialistic cause or intentions in Central America or wherever.
and therefore they were rejecting that on the basis of an anti-imperialist pitch.
Well, you know, I would add they're by far an extremely small minority.
I think most, the greatest percentage of vets were thought monuments of some positive notoriety were due.

To pull almost a quote out of their 1982 issue, they say the true forgotten heroes were actually the VC, where they taught the anti-war movement how to rebel against the imperialists who forced them to crawl and march forward.
Well, I think that's a lot of horse shit, and you can quote me on that.
The VC slaughtered so many people, the bloodbath that we wanted to prevent occurring.
We were protesting against the war, which we believed was coming once we withdrew.
It did come, but I don't think anyone realized the extent of it.
The killing fields kind of mentality that existed in Laos and Cambodia, as well as Vietnam, it's hard to compliment the VCs.
on their contributions to humanity when the greatest thing they've done is kill each other since we've left the country and kill their neighboring Cambodians.
I certainly wouldn't compliment the VC on standing up.
This country's had a 200-year reputation for standing up.
Just reflects perhaps the radical nature.
I think it reflects the extremely radical nature.
Okay.

One more, I guess, local question, and that is in dealing in Mankato or the Twin Cities, did you have any problems with the mayor, like Stenvig in Minneapolis, or were most people pretty cooperative as far as getting a permit to march or things thereof?
Had too much problem.
Of course, you're not going to put that in.
No.
We never had too much problem in Mankato, and I really don't think that we had a whole lot of problem in Minneapolis-St. Paul.
We always policed ourselves up and were dedicated, nonviolent, and people didn't dread to see us coming because we didn't leave an aftermath.
The Mayor Stenvig in Minneapolis, I don't know, he didn't do anything in denying VVAW any of the requests that we submitted to march or to protest or to meet.
He, I believe that he was a little less considerate of some of the other organizations.
but politically he didn't think it was a good idea to tangle with the vets group because we really hadn't done anything bad.

In Mankato, the police chief so identified, was so distraught with the conduct of the war, and it's continuing, and the misinformation and disinformation that the government and the military published that once he
reached that position, he resigned from the Air Force Reserve, where he'd had an 18-year career at that point, and had been a Korean War vet.
And he lost his pension and other rights on account of it, but he so firmly identified.
He also, we at Mankato did a couple of things.
One of them was we conducted a
I think it amounted to about a 62-day vigil at the post office where we maintained a continuous presence.
And he nor the police or anyone other than individual citizens hassled us there.
The most violent thing that occurred was the members of the peace organizations occupied a bridge
between Mankato and North Mankato, and it was a primary link of travel for folks coming in between the two cities.
Occupied it for one afternoon, and the highway patrol eventually, with the sheriff and police, had to arrest a number of folks.
Okay.
Now, when did you leave to wrap up?
You left the VVAW, when?
Or at least your position as regional director?
Or did the movement just fold?
The movement just folded.
There was no subsequent election of anyone after that.
I think the tape's about to run out too.
About ten minutes.
Well, with the folding of the organization then, how would you view your accomplishments with what you had intended to do?
Monumental on a level with Lincoln, Jefferson, Washington, and Christ.
Seriously.
I think in this region, we accomplished what we set out to do.
I think we did a good job.
We were persistent.
We maintained a steady image.
It was a hard time for Vietnam veterans.
Drugs were coming in.
A lot of Vietnam veterans fell prey to drugs.
We managed to keep, to disassociate drugs and VVAW.
We managed to keep veterans who held jobs and went to school associated with VVAW.
On the national level, I think they fell prey to drugs and the radical influences, and it seemed that movements have a way of going that way.
It's been my own personal experience.
You look at almost any movement, the more radicals take over for a while and the movement goes downhill.
and disintegrates.
For example, currently the women's movement, they're making much less radical overtures because they realize they've turned off a number of people and they're politically not going to achieve things.
We politically added a credibility to the position that we were not winning the war, we were not achieving Vietnamizations,
that the statistical body count analysis was false, was a false premise, which was supported by McNamara, who subsequently has proclaimed that he regrets that, that it was a mistake.
Wes Moreland withdrew his suit, his libel suit against CBS, clearly indicating that he felt like he had to go through the motions but knew he couldn't win.

And there was just too much evidence that at various levels, various people suppressed information, passed on doctored information, and the position we took that this was going on was a true position.
And believing in the democratic process, we wanted to talk this over and get that information out, and we accomplished that.
Okay.
It seems then that you're pretty favorable about what the Midwest region did based on this Midwest liberalism, which you seem to say was best typified by Kerry.
John Kerry?
John Kerry from Massachusetts.
And then you have second thoughts, or you withhold some of that enthusiasm as far as the movement as a national movement.
Yeah.
I wouldn't say it was best typified by John Kerry, because he's an Easterner and really didn't have his finger on the pulse of what was happening out here.
He was by far the most articulate spokesman that VVAW had surface on any national level.
And on the national level, I think that the radical elements controlled and that I don't know what these people were up to.
And I don't know who supported them.
And I didn't trust them.
And if the members here had gotten the chance to personally meet them and associate with them, the members here would not have condoned them and did not.
We got home.
We discussed it.
That was it.
We were disgusted.
We were through with National VVAW.

But we continued our efforts because we weren't sure what had happened, whether the FBI had caused this radical group nationally, whether it didn't matter to us who it was, our point was still the same.
Let's continue the dialogue.
It's best for the country.
Right.
And with the end of the war, logically the end of the movement.
Yes.
Some people have likened me to a modern-day Christ, and I want to say that I don't think that's true.
Well, then thank you very much for the interview, and hopefully the FBI doesn't read this.
How many years will it be before I get the transcript of this one?
Well, hopefully not more than the usual two.
Thank you.
Thank you.
